An index than the ring is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index than the ring are exposed to a lower risk of cancer of the prostate.
That is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British journal Cancer.
That may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
" Our findings show that the length of the finger serves as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, particularly for men before 60 years ," declared the study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Research on the cancer at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should take the test of prostate cancer, including combined with the genetic risk or other factors aggrâvants as the antécedents family health, added Eeles.
During the period of 1994-2009 it followed with his colleagues in Britain more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right hand shorter than the ring.
For them, as for 19 per cent of those who had the fingers of the same length, it was found the same likelihood of cancer of the prostate.
In the case of those who had the longest that ring the risk is, however, dropped to 33 percent for men before 60 years in the risk rose to 87 per cent.
The report length of two fingers - trained during the prenatal period - states of different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
A less testosterone is a index.
previous research had shown that it is precisely the testosterone that development aid cancer of the prostate.
The pprofesseur Vacla Paces, généticien Czech renowned and former president of the National Academy of Sciences, said to KTC that he is aware of this study but does not, apparently, that the relationship between the length and the cancer is " completely demonstrated ."
