Obama is cracking down on new oil drilling
There will be no new drilling for oil in the Gulf of Mexico off the Florida coast, south-east of the United States, in the years to come.
The Government Washington delivered a ban equivalent, and permanently cancelled its initial plans.
Even off the Atlantic coast, new drilling remain for the time being banned.
The Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar has made the announcement Wednesday.
It is the explosion, in April, of the drilling platform " Deepwater Horizon " is at the origin of this strict prohibition. Act must continue at least for the next five years.
Given this accident which claimed the lives of 11 employees and led to the greatest environmental disaster of the United States, President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and industry, has indicated that it is willing to allow new drilling in the eastern Gulf of Mexico.
supporters of this solution attempt to reduce US dependence on foreign countries for oil supplies.
The question of who is the responsibility of the oil slick devastating in golf is not, so far, definitively resolved.
The British oil group, which is facing claims of several billion, is at the centre of allegations.
A commission of inquiry set up by Obama must submit its conclusions in December.
In October, the Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar had lifted the suspension of drilling declared after the explosion of the platform.
Following this decision, various oil groups immediately submitted applications to new drilling projects.
With more stringent control measures and procedures more severe, Obama and Salazar want to prevent another disaster.
