The democratic routine
The support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as to private enterprise.
The crime became greater concern that unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as influential as the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarómetro poll taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Given that the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it follows the change of attitude in the region.
Two elements in the poll results this year, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the enough sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
The support for democracy has risen significantly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see table 1).
For example in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a minimum of 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy rebounded after a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries of the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the average (see chart 2).
Some 44 per cent of the region expressed satisfaction with the way in which democracy in their countries worked in practice; it was the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase on the 25 per cent in 2001 (Chart 3)
Thirty-four percent said they had confidence in Parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but in significant increase from 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America have shaken the support to democracy.
If it stood during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries have suffered only a brief recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a network of social security has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again this year to 32 per cent.)
But mood varies considerably from one country to another (see chart 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, has resulted in a widespread feeling of progress
What is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more harsh and violent crime has increased.
Only for the second time since the survey was started more than respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited the crime rather than the unemployment as the most important issue facing their countries (see chart 5).
About 31 per cent say that they or a close have been the victim of a crime over the past year; however, this figure is lower than the 38 per cent last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in the rise of support for private enterprise and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is essential for the development, compared to 56% in 2007 (see chart 6).
Some 58 per cent believed that the market economy is the only system that will make them developed countries, against 47 per cent last year.
Interestingly, 62 per cent of respondents in Venezuela are of the opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); even if their president, Hugo Chavez, expropriating many businesses closed.
Brazil is the greatest leader in the region, mentioned by 19 per cent (up from 18 percent last year -RRB - followed by the USA (9% , unchanged compared to last year) and Venezuela (9% , a decrease of 11% for the year)
but the United States is considered to be the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and throughout much of Central America, while Venezuela has this distinction in Ecuador, Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A vote soiled
Nobody expected to have perfect general elections on 28 November.
But it was much worse than the " outsiders " who wanted to help the stricken country and plunged in fear.
The ballot boxes and a new election ballots scattered in the goutières, polling ransacked and intimidation
The polling stations opened late in the evening.
Many Hatïens, including many who were displaced following the earthquake in January, roamed the neighbourhood to find where vote.
Some of them eventually abandon.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several alleged favourites, have denounced the fraud and have called for the cancellation of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, exploded across the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, the senior official with the United Nations, said the event as " a pretty good in many respects election ."
observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean have carefully stated that they " believe that these irregularities, as serious, had necessarily invalidated the process ."
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are indebted to René Préval, unpopular outgoing president, and its candidate, Jude Célestin, must announce preliminary results on 7 December.
The second round expected is scheduled for January.
Any hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial appeal for the vote to be annulled.
But there may be problems if Mr. Célestin, which has little or no visible support among voters, is said by the electoral authority as having reached the second toura reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic, raging, and more than 1 million of the earthquake survivors who are still living in tents, it was feared that the participation would.
Accordingly, many Haitïens wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disruption.
About 250,000 identity cards, necessary to vote, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The issue is important.
The donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in the rebuilding of Haiti.
And so, it is clear, Haitians are themselves.
The tip to the centre
weeks after becoming a suddenly widow, Cristina Fernández, Argentine President, received a wave of public sympathy has improved its approval rate of 20 points, to over 50 per cent, its highest level since it was elected in 2007.
Yet turn that into a successful campaign for a second term at an election next year could depend on the choice of Ms. Fernández, apparently in mourning, that it would abandon the intransigence of her late husband's predecessor, and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs remain unclear.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to manage the economic policy, even after his wife succeeded as president, used to prepare budgets that underestimates the income tax, economic growth and inflation.
This gave the first couple to spend extra income at will.
The government of Ms. Fernández has lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has collapsed in disarray following the death of Mr. Kirchner of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some dissident members of the movement péroniste in power have joined Ms. Fernández.
But after chaotic meetings (where a Parliamentary slapped in the face one of its peers and others have accused the government of corruption -RRB - the Congress does not have to approve the budget 2011.
" I will not argue, " said the president.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the President once more flexibility to spend at will.
The economy overheating widely: it is likely to grow by nearly 9 per cent this year.
The official rate of inflation now stands at 11.1 per cent but many private estimates and wage demands of unions, see this figure close to 30% .
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic meltdown, has made a priority of growth and the reduction of poverty, rather than the control of inflation.
It has refused to deal with the IMF, it had harassed the private sector and served the INDEC, the statistical office, which had official falsifications of statistics on inflation.
Ms. Fernández can with moderate these policies?
It called for talks between the companies and union leaders.
And officials say they want to limit wage increases in the next year to 18 per cent.
The economy has been driven by high world prices for agricultural exports to Argentina.
But inflation has eroded the boost to growth following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
That is perhaps why Ms. Fernández shows signs of wanting to restore financial relations of Argentina to the rest of the world.
. This year, the government has concluded an agreement with bondholders who had rejected an earlier restructuring of debt on which Argentina had not paid its deadlines in 2001.
Now Ms. Fernández seems to be edging towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 trillion.
The Kirchner have always insisted that they could involve monitoring by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the Economics Minister, announced that the Fund would provide a " technical assistance " to develop a new national index of consumer prices; what appears to be a prelude to the INDEC.
It is not clear whether Mrs. Fernández wants to remain in politics beyond the end of his mandate, now that her husband is no longer at his side.
If it does, it needs to win the support of the middle class, including the kirchnerisme is very advocated.
When Argentines are back from their summer holidays in March, the wave of sympathy for it will have receded.
If it wants to win another election, it would have to decide whether to repudiate or not, quietly, many policies of her husband.
