A microbe tolerant arsenic raises the possibility of new forms of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the scope to find new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered bacteria unusual here on Earth, they say it shows that life has opportunities beyond the major elements that have been regarded as essential.
" This body has a dual capacity. "
" It can be developed with phosphorous, with arsenic. "
" That is why it is very special, even if it is far from being a form of life really " foreign ," commented on Paul Davies C. W. of the University of Arizona State, co-author of the report in the online edition of Thursday in the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: the carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacteria found in the Mono Lake in California, is able to continue to grow after replaced the phosphorus arsenic.
" One wonders what is still possible, " said Ariel Anbar D. University of Arizona State, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, about what life is, said Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
however, announced a press conference to discuss, who did not disclose details of the discovery, has led to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report would disclose the discovery of alien life.
This has not been the case.
The discovery shows that, in other global environments, the agencies might be able to use other elements to activate the biochemistry and that the whole " standard ," that we are absolutely necessary for life, could not be established ," commented on Charles Cockell, a professor at the Institute of scientific research and spacial, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
" This work is again because it shows the substitution of a fundamental element to the other in biochemistry and the biochemical structure, added Cockell.
This was not an accidental discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon Institute of Astrologie NASA, which conducted the study, has chosen the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
The arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, it has speculated that microbe exposed to two substances might be able to substitute.
" The arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behaviour is very similar to that of phosphorus. "
" As a result, the agencies have difficult to separate these elements separately. "
" But arsenic is sufficiently different to that it is not working exactly as phosphorus; it cuts inside and, in a way, gum the biochemical machine, " said Anbar.
Researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed to increased concentrations of arsenic that she was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with the phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic to place raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic may occur naturally, is also on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that the arsenic could be replaced by the phosphorus, was not new, but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
The arsenic was more frequent at the beginning of the existence of the earth, it says, researchers have speculated that the first forms of life could have used.
This suggests that there may be other ways of life, not just how life on Earth was formed early, " said Foster, who was not part of the research team Wolfe-Simon.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
