Prosecutors do not inculperont not Senator Ensign
The Ministry of Justice prosecutors have lifted the criminal charges on Senator John Ensign, arising out of a case linked to a assistant a former campaign and in its efforts to obtain a lobbying for the husband of the woman, have anoncé Wednesday, lawyers Senator.
The decision brings to a close the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Republican Nevada which was seen as a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential until the scandal surrounding his case to make headlines national last year and damage to his career.
Mr. room Ensign said he was " very pleased " with the decision, the result of a survey a year.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Lawyers for Mr. Ensign stated that the Ministry of Justice had " informed that Senator Ensign was more investigation and that it did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case. "
The Ministry of Justice has refrained from comment on this subject.
The announcement has come as something of a surprise for many ethics lawyers outside the Ministry of Justice that there would be significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign have conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first reported in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain a lucrative lobbying work to earn the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, in the case of Senator with it.
Ms. Hampton once served as Treasurer during a campaign of Ensign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of donors policies to find work for Mr. Hampton and then he defended their rights after they have hired Mr. Hampton for lobbying for them; according to documents and interviews.
Given that Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was banned for a year by the lobby of his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
The ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to be in contradiction with the so-called revolving door of lobbying.
According to the evidence has been made public, " there seems to be a prima facie case of conspiracy to rape and serious violation of the law of the revolving door, " said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of an investigation by the Government.
Although the judge Ministry has refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the case Ensign, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers have said that the Ministry appeared to be wary of political prosecution after a number of setbacks cashed high-level its public integrity section, including the decision last year to dismiss the case against the former senator Ted Stevens accused of misconduct prosecution.
federal prosecutors have clearly afraid to take the weapons, said Melanie he, the Director-General for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
" This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don 't apply to them, " she added.
Paul Coggins, principal of Mr. lawyer Ensign, said in an interview that he had received on Monday, a telephone call from a prosecutor of the Ministry of Justice and monitoring the following day, saying that the ministry did not seek charges against his client.
The team of lawyers for Mr. Ensign had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the Senator, as his office has reaffirmed Wednesday, in a statement, " had acted in accordance with the law. "
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments it had made to the service.
" I am not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Ministry of Justice, except to say that we believe that they took the right decision ," at.
last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to abandon an independent investigation following a complaint by the ethics group, claiming that the payment of $96.000 by parents of Mr. Ensign to Hampton violated the federal election law.
The Electoral Commission said that it had insufficient evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a Nevada who has long supported Senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign assisted Mr. Hampton to find lobbying.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company hosted Mr Hampton as a lobbyist, the head of Mr. Ensign, John Lopez, provided with Mr. Hampton and told her that he " martelait " the Ministry of the Interior on an issue in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another customer in Nevada, Allegiant Air, and it has asked the secretary of transport to set a meeting on behalf of the airline after hired Mr. Hampton to lobbying.
When the new case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his post of leader the fourth Republican in the Senate.
After maintained a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, has said that the senator had hoped that the ethics committee quickly follow the example of the Ministry of Justice and put an end to its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, said.
The appeal of Cheshire league table to Twitter
A handful of them were kick away in rows of the courtroom.
They send all minutes of reports of horrific testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defence said that there were more than 140 000 messages on the case of rape and children tied to their beds in a house was set on fire.
Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of killing three members of a Cheshire family in Connecticut, should lead to a formal end where the judge imposed the death sentence passed by the jury.
But lawyers for Mr. Hayes have already filed the court that outlines the appeal to the courts for years.
What is provocative, is that the intense reports on the trial - and the widespread use and extended by journalists of Twitter - have created an atmosphere of circus, a saturation so widespread and instant with incendiary details that the jury was not influenced by the passions of the public.
The demand could push the appeal judges to discuss the question of whether the new technologies require new rules in the courtroom.
" I experienced at this trial; I think there is a real danger, the introduction of new technologies in the courtroom violates human rights to a fair trial, " said Thomas J. Ullmann, lawyer for Mr. Hayes, chief lawyer.
The trial judge, Jon C. blue Superior Court has their answers rejected the claims in the judgment last week, saying that the media were " carefully controlled " and that there was no evidence that the jury had been driven by passion.
But that does not appear to be the last word on the issue.
The appellate courts recognize for decades that the media coverage of the notorious cases may raise questions about the fairness of the trial.
In a trial of 1966, the United States Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a ostéopathe Cleveland, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, in its decision that there was a " carnival atmosphere " because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television and film " The fugitive.
Some lawyers have said that appellate courts to review half a century later the conviction of Mr. Hayes may be curious given the argument that new rules may be needed to manage the media courtroom, unimaginable to the case of Dr. Sheppard.
" There is a reason to worry about the impact of new media in the trial of major, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at the Stanford School of Law who has studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it was arbitrarily applied.
Professor Donohue claims that some appeal judges may be intrigued by the idea that the limitation of instant communication from the courtroom could lead to more fair trials.
Twitter case is only one of many described by lawyers for Mr. Hayes, likely to be discussed during the years; delaying the execution.
defence lawyers say also, for example, that Mr. Hayes suffered injury when the judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reaction of potential jurors in lurid photos of criminal scenes in the selection of the jury.
Some jurors said they had been horrified by the photos of victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11 years ago.
defence lawyers argue that they are also challenging the constitutionality of the death penalty and that they will argue that the judge wrongly deported one juror, which had been critical to prosecutors, and that he improperly put pressure for a verdict by taking the unusual decision to persuade the jury to deliberate in a weekend.
The jurors had not been kidnapped.
But their arguments on the intense media coverage of the trials could be the greatest source of interest.
They noted in a protest against the verdict, filed last month that dominated the media scene in Connecticut and that it was discussed during the election campaign by the candidates for the post of governor and U.S. Senate.
They have maintained that the computer media continued to fan the flames of the emotion of the case.
" The scramble daily tweets media, cameras and journalists to the palace of justice ," said lawyers, " not resembled nothing had been seen here in New Haven, and perhaps even at the national level. "
Their emphasis on the system Twitter is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists have said that the affirmation that the new instant were more incendiary that releases handed over more slowly, was a luddiste that much diminished the Court policy governing media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers have said that the call étaitent often lured by arguments that the social and technological change required an adjustment by the courts.
Lawyers for Mr. Hayes insist on this claim.
In their case, they refer to the decision of the Supreme Court of 1966, which had overturned the conviction of Dr. Sheppard in media coverage of the trial and they indicated that they invoke the need of new rules for the new media.
" This case ," said they ," is that of Sheppard v. Maxwell in the 21st century. "
The civility can bring the divisions?
After a campaign marked by the invective and the negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of a genuine bipartisan cooperation or an illusory time before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress has produced no breakthrough on the major issues that need to be addressed during the session of " lame duck ."
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion on differences of both parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibility, rather than another episode where each side to score points. vacuum rating point supporter.
Wednesday public meeting of the committee on the deficit of President was equally civilized, despite political differences remain between the States.
It seems clear that the interaction of several months has created a mutual respect across the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides the members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two parties are now in a period of testing and tested mutual for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a partisan war renewed.
That is why the meeting Tuesday and the subsequent comments of participants have unveiled a minimum requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the environment that existed in the past two years.
Whether taxation, costs, health care or the rights, the two parties are miles away.
Yet, the election of November had moderate Washington, at least in the short term.
" There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone, " said Pete Wehner, an official of the Bush administration, now in the Centre of ethical and public policy.
" It is inevitable after the elections.
The elections raise partisan passions and then they estomptent.
That is good. "
on certain issues, including those on the agenda of the " lame duck ," Republicans and Democrats had no choice but to find a solution.
The Bush tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of it.
The two parties want to find a way to preserve some or all, temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, not least because the Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing the unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After the meeting Tuesday at the White House, more optimism over a possible agreement on issues raised during the session on the " lame duck ," with the ratification of the pact " New START.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution, warns that a successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the session " blade duck " does not ménera not necessarily better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
" Once the things that need to be made for the psychology in the short term will be one of confrontation, " he said.
Wehner has also expressed scepticism widely shared view that civilisation would lead to genuine cooperation.
" I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pré-spectacle or a shadow-boxing compared to the main event in 2012, at.
The reasons are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and voters who tea that contributed to its creation.
However Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they should try to live up to their promise to reduce public spending and to repeal the new law on health care.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the committee of the deficit which include reforming the tax code and increasing some taxes, raise the retirement age and reducing expenditure.
The co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles has chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and themselves, imposed the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in committee, made up of 18 members, to make their plan as a formal recommendation, and they have been struggling to reach this number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected representatives of the group, which suggests that it on tax issues, at least today, few grounds or willingness to compromise.
Galston provides two phases in the fighting between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first will next year in the form of clashes supporters, given that the Republican contest Obama budget, taxes and health care; and then be followed by a period of great bipartisan cooperation.
What is the cause of change?
The public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still wants to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, when the two parties will observe carefully public reaction.
Anyone deemed in loss should change course and compromise.
But this would be an optimistic view.
The partisanship and the polarization are higher today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a more ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress that there were between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, militants from both parties see 2010 as a prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it much more effort on the part of both parties to find common ground on the issues that divide them yet.
