The veterans of the Khmer Rouge forced to confront the past
In a classroom poorly informed with concrete walls derelict sheds of poor quality, the director of the secondary school of Anlong Veng referred to the man who had built, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
" Everyone here like Ta Mok. "
" It was a good leader; and he cared for his people, " said Sreng Kor My, aged 42.
Known as " the butcher " for its brutality, when he was head of the Khmer Rouge, the commander remains popular in this isolated bastion of former Khmer Rouge in north-west Cambodia where it has built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
This year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge went to the Government, the loyalty is finally challenged to Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum of truth and reconciliation has allowed victims to respond publicly to people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government has distributed a manual of high school, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of his former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, jointly run with the United Nations, made its first award on a former member of the Khmer Rouge, condemning, to 35 years in prison, the former leader of the notorious torture centre of Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch.
Faced with these developments, the anxiety has increased to veterans of the Khmer Rouge to Anlong Veng; complicating the efforts of reconciliation and their wills to reintegrate into society.
" resentment and fear among former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything, " said Chhang Youk, director of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia, an independent agency that conducts research on the regime.
" For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil. "
" The situation creates divisions within families. "
Under the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease and overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the government of Pol Pot-Unis in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled Cambodia's border with Thailand.
Here, they launched an insurgency that has lasted until the last of the movements visit in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, Ieng Sary ran the guerrillas from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a response to Anlong Veng.
, however, in the mid-1990s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the United Nations has led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of fighters Khmer Rouge have begun to defect to the government, culminating in the capitulations Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, which had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most veterans of the Khmer Rouge have sunk in abject poverty, common in rural Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although some officers elite Khmer Rouge have kept their posts of local leader in exchange for the weapons, it is not qualified farmers on low rank and file.
" These people have received very little follow-up after the capitulation, " said Sok Leang Centre for justice and reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
" They are soaked with environmentally ideology utopian land regime. "
" They were high in a framework in which to do business is a foreign concept. "
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before in 1998 as poor rice farmer.
" The life under the Khmer Rouge was good, " he said.
" Ta Mok has everyone. "
But now, life is difficult because we need to meet our own needs. "
The Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also caused concern here.
The court should, at the beginning of next year, begin the trial of Nuon Chea Khieu Samphan, and Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge.
The Court's mandate is to try senior leaders of the crimes but it has not said if he continued beyond these four cases.
It needed more to calm fears to Anlong Veng.
The recent media speculation turned towards Im Chaem, aged 64, former head of district in the province of Banteay Meanchey under the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers Documentation Centre of Cambodia that it had supervised the construction of the dam Trapeang Thma, a project where thousands of workers forced died.
recently at a torrid evening, Im Chaem amounted to field near its wooden house on poles on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the grass desséchée, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past in the Khmer Rouge.
If the court convened, it says, it refuses to go.
" Cambodia is peaceful and stable " at it.
" If there was more to stay, there will be war. "
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability could happen if the court had several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
" Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past at.
But the past is all that Cambodia must do to move forward, said Youk Chhang, the documentation centre.
" The reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect the broken pieces, he said.
" We must put the pieces together so that we can understand. "
The centre has produced the first manual approved by the Government on the Khmer Rouge, " A history of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages. "
It distributed to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history books of the Ministry of Education, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, young people Anlong Veng are only a few details of the Khmer Rouge, in spite of the city's links to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at the high school Anlong Veng, said that the new book helps students to understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted with scepticism when he returned with the book at home to study.
" My family rejected many parts of the handbook and the court, " he said.
" They are wary because they do not know exactly how many people the court will continue. "
Such resistance has made the complex and difficult reconciliation process, said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the manual and the court is beginning to have an impact, at.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retain a atrait powerful here.
In the mountains of Dangrek, a road, invaded by weeds and littered with plastic bags, led to a rectangle of black soot, under a tin roof rouillée.
The body of Pol Pot was burned on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, age 31, selling mobile phones in roadside, has said that she did not know very little about the man who has been cremated.
" But it has a great spirit; and many people go there to ask, said.
It was the anniversary of Nuom Sothea and, later that day -là, it plans to walk to the last resting place of Pol Pot where it would leave a mature mix of bananas in the hope of providing the opportunity.
Belarus is prepared to give up its stock of uranium
the Belarus government has announced Wednesday that it would abandon its stock of highly enriched uranium, a key ingredient to the nuclear weapons; this decision is part of a surprise victory of President Obama's campaign to secure nuclear materials around the world
The agreement was disclosed in a joint statement issued after Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met by the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Belarus, Sergei Martynov, on the sidelines of a summit on the Council.
The US government had tried for years to persuade the Belarus to renounce the highly enriched uranium and appeared to have reached the horizon last spring.
But American officials have told the Washington Post that some classified operations have been conducted with Belarus in the past two months to eliminate 187 pounds of uranium from a research centre of Belarus.
This paved the way for an agreement on Wednesday to eliminate the rest of the field of about £ 500, according to an official who spoke about the condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the issue.
The agreement appears to be one of the most important results of the Nuclear Safety Summit of 47 nations, held at the initiative of Obama; Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it was good to get an invitation to the former Soviet republic following the summit in 2012.
" I am really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the summit of nuclear security of 2012 nuclear Council Summit. "
" It is evidence that this process works, " said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for global security, a group of nuclear safety.
Clinton has called the agreement " very significant, important " by the Belarus.
Obama has pledged to Prague in April 2009 to secure all vulnerable nuclear materials around the world in the next four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries to get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
The Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries have done so under the administration of George W. Bush.
When Summit on the nuclear safety of Obama, the Belarusian president, Alexander Lukashenko, stated that the nation would agree not to its uranium.
" We have kept highly enriched uranium, hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially of uranium and low-enriched uranium ," he told Mr. Lukashenko.
" This is our product. .. We are not going to manufacture dirty bombs, and we will sell it to anyone. "
" We are going to use for research purposes. "
Belarus is close to the United States a few months ago; however, expressing interest in reaching an agreement.
The first implemented to eliminate uranium Belarus, in October, has been particularly complicated because the material had been slightly spent, said officials.
It was loaded on a special train who has travelled more than 1 300 miles to a facility in Russia to be stored and eliminated, said officials.
The second round was completed Monday and was carried out by plane, according to officials.
The US government spent $13 million in its efforts, largely to replace the research of Belarus with low-enriched uranium; inadequate for the weapons.
" A careful coordination and organization have been implemented in order to strengthen the confidence "; leading to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, a department of energy specialist in the World Threat Reduction.
According to Study Centre estimates of Nonprolifération James Martin, the Belarus this year at least 88 pounds of uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
The Belarus seeks to eliminate its stocks by 2012, according to a joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly because of the harsh repression by Lukashenko of Human Rights.
But the statement Wednesday suggested a potential revival.
" While welcoming the progress on these issues of global security, the United States and Belarus have recognized that a greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus were essential to improve bilateral relations; and essential for the progress of the country and its citizens ," she said.
