Red Bull triumph in F1 with a secret weapon of Siemens
A software creates improvements on cars in real time.
As soon as Red Bull es entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this sélecte universe of the speed has been marked by surprise and the success.
In a first time, nobody has taken into account the options of a new stable which had just happen, despite the upward trajectory of recent seasons, the past November, in the last phase of the championship they bet on the triumph of Ferrari of Fernando Alonso.
Without down the skill as pilot champion, the German Sebastien Vette, the capacity of the Renault engine that drives his car, in the world of Formula 1 legend spoke of the " secret weapon " that the multinational company Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to transform it into a winning team.
It is in fact a powerful software simulation process that the German company launched on the market in 2007 with very distant goals of the top-class automobilistique.
Appointed PLM, this powerful instrument technology has been used to create networks of mounting manufacturing factories, power stations, high precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce, simulate faithfully the product or process before the construction of a real, thereby avoiding defects and avoidable costs.
PLM facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi or more famous Nissan commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, responsible for the industrial division of Siemens, said the fact that the use of this instrument in its plant in Formula 1 has helped Red Bull to create and execute " in for a few hours, almost in real time ," the changes, changes and improvements detected during racing and tests.
Russwurm explained that the stables of the year 1992 had an average of 10 technicians in their teams was able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements on the vehicles each season.
In the Red Bull team are now working 180 young professionals from high qualifications which, powerful computer equipment and are planning any sort of changes on the bolides.
The leader of Siemens explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of bolides of Red Bull except the engine, which is solely responsible for Renault.
We change the materials, fuel, aerodynamics and security.
The can move from the virtual reality of reality simulator in less than 24 hours, through advanced systems of production by laser and autoclaves high technology.
As single limitation of this madness of technological development there is the amount of 40 million dollars each team Formula 1 can spend as limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has established the high technology to create and produce its bolides in a town 50 miles from London.
These are two buildings where the visits, especially for journalists, are limited.
Everything that is happening there is considered " top secret ."
The personnel for this duty account 580 people, ci-inclus two pilot, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of the Formula 1 Red Bull, perhaps, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Between the tremendous technological resources that the energy drinks is at the service of its participation in the channels, there are other hidden actors, whose work is invaluable and zero visibility.
factory technology director, Steve Nevey, claims that five years ago you could say that the progress of R+D in racing cars were the 50 per cent of victories and the pilot were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have changed and technology represents 85% of success, while the pilot make the 15% of the value added.
Nevey admit that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computer, because " they are unpredictable gladiators.
