The radio broadcaster of Quebec Stéphane Dupont suffered a partial setbacks before the Council of broadcasting standards (Central Commission) for controversial remarks on social assistance and Haitians on his bad language in waves.
The Central Commission judge that he and his team of CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their views, but some of the information contained inaccurate on social assistance, negative Haitians and vulgar language which is not appropriate for broadcasts during the day.
The Council has also concluded that a debate on suicide, including the dissemination of two people who were killed themselves, have not violated codes on the radio.
The Central Commission had received several complaints about comments made during broadcasts between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made following a complaint from the Front in people attended the Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts cited in the programme were inaccurate.
The leaders must submit solid information, rather than misleading.
With regard to suicide, the moderator Stéphane Dupont had estimated that suicide is a cowardly act.
The majority of the members of the Committee concluded that the message was that the suicide should not be seen as a solution to the problems of life.
" The majority of the Committee believes that the episodes in " Dupont lunch " addressed a delicate subject of fair and appropriate way. "
No blame had been accepted.
The latest dispute was on statements following the earthquake in Haiti.
Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort then engaged in a standoff media had been a great deal of response.
The moderator CHOI stated that there had been no donation to help Haitians because we could not know with certainty that the needy people really receive money.
The Committee believes that these comments were not abusive, but their cumulative effect is unduly negative representation of Haitians.
" I have served my suspension of three days. "
" My issue is free for a year and a half, " said the leader.
In the decisions, the Committee denounced the dissemination of bad language.
In each case, the broadcaster CHOI-FM worked " beyond its obligation ."
consequences are minimal, for the station, which will, among other things, announce these decisions once during the prime-time within three days.
