No online games for the young Koreans past midnight
The South Korean government will adopt a " Cinderella " that will prohibit adolescents to play games online after midnight to block their access, said government officials.
A bill will be submitted to Parliament in December to ask companies to online games to block access to these games after midnight, young people under the age of 16 years, said representatives from the ministries of culture and the family.
" Many children play in these games all night and then learning difficulties at school and have a normal life during the day. "
" We believe that this law is needed to ensure their health and their right to sleep ," told the AFP Jo Rin, the ministerial responsibility for the bill.
The online games will again be available to 6 a.m.
companies will have a year to prepare for the implementation of the law, he said.
The government also plans to ask companies to limit the time of daily access to these games for young people whose parents request, added the responsible.
It will also be available to people who are calling for free software which limit the time spent on the Internet.
South Korea is one of the more " connected " and the newspapers reported regularly events related to extensive use of the Internet.
The country is also the undisputed champion of global competitions of online gambling.
In November, the South Korea won four gold medals at the World Cyber Games, to 58 other nations.
