Euro: the ECB forced to maintain its purchases of government securities
The last meeting of the Governing Council of the European Central Bank (ECB) of the year should be the opportunity to clarify the exit of crisis or, at least, to announce the arrest of a number of operations unconventional monetary policy which must be achèver at the end of the year.
European sovereign debt crisis, the institute of Frankfurt may not allow itself to be sweeping under penalty of worsen a situation more tense today on the European bond markets.
The cost would be higher.
Yesterday, at a press conference, the French Finance Minister, Christine Lagarde, has welcomed the active role played by the ECB in favour of the resolution of the debt crisis of states in Europe.
She did not want to say whether they believed that the central bank should do more, increasing by example its programme of buying sovereign bond.
" I reserve my reflection in my European partners (...) ."
The eve, in Brussels, during his hearing by the Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs of the European Parliament, the President of the ECB, Jean-Claude Trichet, has not shown more reticent to its intentions, simply stating that the programme of buying securities State on the secondary market continues " and that " we will see what we decide " at the meeting on Thursday.
Only certainty: the ECB is going to keep its main interest rate unchanged at 1 per cent, the lowest level on record since May 2009.
In fact, purchases of government bonds by the ECB have doubled last week, about 1.35 billion euros.
And, according to the indiscretions of market operators, it would have made new purchases of Irish titles and Portuguese, yesterday.
In total, the central banks of the Eurosystem purchased for 67 billion euros since May 2010.
Among the market operators, the expectations of further purchases are clear (see page 29).
Economists either do not expect significant change of course.
operations of loans to more than three months have already disappeared from the arsenal of the ECB, the Commission still unlimited cash benefits according to generous conditions and for periods from a week to three months.
Economists are now expecting this device will be extended by a few months.
" I cannot imagine that it changes significantly its programme. "
" Otherwise it would take the risk of new tensions in the short term, said Michael Schubert, economist Commerzbank.
" progressive exit announced during the first quarter of 2011 seems more likely, anticipates its side Norbert Bräms, economist at Sal.
Oppenheim.
